    label: "Spending Optimization",
    screenshot: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1554224155-6726b3ff858f?w=600&q=80",
    screenshotAlt: "Budget optimization and allocation",
    content: `**Military Spending:**\n- < 10%: Attrition — units decline over time\n- 10–20%: Maintenance — current military sustained\n- 20–35%: Building — slow military growth\n- 35–50%: Power growth — significant military gain\n- > 50%: Economic drag — GDP and trust penalties\n\nRecommended: 20–30% in peacetime, 35–45% during active conflict.\n\n**Education Spending:**\n- < 10%: Minimal — near-zero TP bonus\n- 10–20%: Base — small TP and school bonuses\n- 20–35%: Optimal — best ROI range\n- 35–45%: High — good returns, slight GDP cost\n- > 45%: Diminishing — high cost, marginal gain\n\nRecommended: 25–35% always. Education is never wasted.\n\n**Combined spending ceiling:**\nMilitary + Education + fixed overhead cannot exceed ~80% of GDP. If you push both to 40%, you're spending 80% before accounting for other costs — high deficit risk.\n\n**Dynamic strategy:**\n- Peacetime: 20% military, 30% education (growth focus)\n- Pre-war: 35% military, 25% education (buildup)\n- Active war: 45% military, 20% education (survival)\n- Post-war rebuild: 15% military, 35% education (recovery)`,
    tips: ["The 25% education sweet spot gives roughly 2× the TP generation of 10% for only a small GDP cost.", "Dropping military below 15% to save credits often costs more in stability penalties than it saves."]
